      • ABOUT THIS STEP COUNETER WATCH: In order to effectively filter out invalid steps caused by irregular movements of the hand, all step counts for single continuous movements less than 10 seconds will be disregarded (if exceeds 10 seconds, the previous step counts will automatically be accumulated).
      • FUNCTIONS: *Calculation of Steps, calories, and mileage(Kilometers and miles can be switched) *Time,date,and week(12/24 hour format switchable) *Alarm and hourly time *Countdown and stopwatch *5 seconds EL bright backlight *30M waterproof
      • MATERIALS: *IP electroplated glossy metal case(available in silver, gold and rose gold) *Step counting sensor made in the USA *Adjustable lightweight breathable steel woven band with stainless steel folding buckle.
      • PRACTICALITY:This pedometer watch uses a large-capacity Japanese-made CR2032 battery, which can last up to 15 months without charging. It also does not require any APP connection and is ready to use any time you want.
      • SUITABLE FOR : This stylish lady's pedometer watch is perfect for almost any occasion. As long as your wrist size is between : 4.33-7.67inch(110-195mm)
      • REASONS FOR STEP COUNT ERRORS: *Irregular walking patterns (walking in crowded areas, stopping and starting while in line, etc.) *Pushing a shopping cart or stroller *Being in a location with frequent vibrations, or riding a bicycle or car *Frequent movement of hands or arms (clapping, fanning oneself, etc.), walking while holding hands, walking with a cane or stick, or any other movement where hands and legs are not coordinated *Non-walking daily activities (cleaning, etc.)

              This is a modal window.

              • Why does my watch screen shows "SHIP" ?

                This is becasue we set the watch to sleep mode to save the battery, you could hold 4 and 8 o'clock buttons about 3 seconds to activate the watch.

              • Does this pedometer watch count steps accurately?

                Yes, but In order to effectively filter out invalid steps caused by irregular movements, single continuous movements less than 10 seconds will be disregarded (if exceeds 10 seconds, the previous step counts will automatically be accumulated).

              • How can I set the time?

                Hold 10 o'clock button 3 seconds into setting mode,then press 8 o'clock button to choose the term you want to change and press 2 or 4 o'clock button to set the value (imperial and metric units switch also here)

              • What to do if the time and steps positionchanged

                You could hold 4 o'clock button 2 second to switch them

              • Can the steps be reset to 0 manually?

                Yes, you could hold 4 o'clock button to clear the steps to 0

              How customer reviews and ratings work

              Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

              To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

              5 out of 5 stars
              A very nice watch!
              I wanted a watch with a pedometer, but did not want any bluetooth capabilities/smart watch. I decided to give this a try. I have been wearing it for about 3 weeks now, and I love it! It was easy to get setup. The steps do seem a little behind, but nothing major. It is easy to adjust to my wrist. Doesn't pinch or rub my wrist at all, which is something I have always dealt with with watches. The brown is a very pretty neutral that looks nice with everything. I am just very pleased, especially for the price.

                5.0 out of 5 stars Cant beat it for the price! No charging needed, nice quality, easy to use
                Reviewed in the United States on October 16, 2024
                Color: SilverStyle: NON-CRYSTALVerified Purchase
                I absolutely love everything about this watch!

                It is exactly what I was looking for. The band is very high-quality braided stainless and was easily adjustable for my small wrist.

                I had no trouble setting it up after reading the directions thoroughly. Its important to note when setting the time that it displays PM after noon, when operating in the 12 hour mode. This matters because it triggers the watch to reset the pedometer and change the date at midnight each day.

                I really wanted a battery-powered watch after my fancy fitness watch died out of the blue and I didnt have my charger with me. I was exasperated and decided I wanted a nice, old-fashioned, battery powered watch that would show me the time and date, count steps, and have timer/stopwatch features, with no app required, no Bluetooth, and no sharing of my personal data. This checked all the boxes. And when it arrived,I was impressed by the appearance and build quality of it. (My husband admired the same qualities about it so he ordered a mens version, and he really likes his too.)

                Unlike my previous fitness watch, this readout of this one displays in a dark enough contrast against the face of the watch that I dont have to create a shadow over the face of it to read the display. I used to have to stop in the middle of my workout if I was outdoors in the bright sun and cup my hand over the face of my watch so I could check the time/date, etc., but not with this one.

                Another really great feature is that the watch uses a plain old CR2032 battery that you can easily switch out yourself. There are four screws on the back of the watch, which I assume will allow access to the battery area when the battery dies. This is another nice feature to the watch, rather than having to take it to the jeweler for a $20 battery change!

                Different reviewers have different opinions regarding the accuracy of the pedometer. However, I know the distance that I walk from measuring it via my car, and from using several different fitness watches prior to this one, and also actually watching it track each step while I walked. As others have stated, sometimes if it has gone dormant while you arent walking, when you stand up and start moving, it will take a second to catch up all the steps (maybe 5 to 7 steps) as it starts tracking, but it will catch up those steps and add them to the total and Ive found it to be pretty accurate. Cant beat it for this price!

              • red-herring12
                3.0 out of 5 stars Great, but be careful with the buttons on the sides
                Reviewed in the United States on January 7, 2025
                Color: GoldStyle: NON-CRYSTALVerified Purchase
                I wanted a pedometer watch that only counted my steps and showed me the time. This was one of a few, and had the most attractive band. It looks like a real watch.

                There are a number of functions, including an alarm you can set, a countdown setting, stopwatch, and chime. The basic setting shows the time and steps. You can toggle to have the display show the time larger and centered, with steps below, or steps large and centered, with time below. The month and day are shown at the top. You can choose between a 12 hour or 24 hour clock.

                Do not throw away the packaging, and read the instructions carefully. It was a little tricky setting the time and getting the display the way I wanted. There are 4 buttons around the sides that have different functions in getting to settings and changing them. It's not 100% intuitive, but many devices have similar routines, and you can set everything with the help of the instructions. You can set it and forget it until it's time to change the clocks every 6 months.

                I found the buttons hard to press and sometimes unresponsive. Recently, one of them fell out, and I can't get it back in place. I had to tape over it to keep it from falling out again. Worried that it will fall out whole I'm out for a walk somewhere.

                The pedometer may be over-counting, compared to my phone. I don't know which is correct. However, I'm not keeping track of steps long-term, just want a general idea of how many I've taken and how far I've walked. I did reduce the star rating because of the accuracy question and the piece falling out. As a simple watch and simple step counter, though, it is working for me.
